<DOC><DOCNO> AP881122-0076 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 1132EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Sun-TimesTalks     11-22 0312</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Sun-Times Talks,0321</SECOND><HEAD>Sun-Times Talks Resume As Union Delays Strike</HEAD><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Negotiators for the Chicago Sun-Times and itseditorial employees returned to the bargaining table today, with theunion saying that a strike threat is still in force.   ``We're not that far apart,'' said Daniel J. Lehmann, spokesmanfor Local 71 of the Chicago Newspaper Guild, which represents 250newsroom employees.   But he said a company offer presented Monday _ calling for no payincrease in the first year of a new contract, followed by 3 percentraises the next two years _ was ``not received favorably'' by guildmembers who met Monday afternoon.   Michael Soll, a Sun-Times spokesman, said: ``I really don't knowthat that's the final offer. They're at the negotiating table. It'sdifficult to know what's going to come out of it.''   The union had set a strike deadline of 2:30 p.m. Monday, butfroze the deadline as negotiations continued Monday and resumed thismorning.   Lehmann, the newspaper's religion writer, reiterated that theguild negotiating committee could call a strike at any time, andSoll said again that the newspaper would continue to publishregardless.   ``There are people in place to step in in the event they'reneeded,'' Soll said.   Before making the new offer Monday, newspaper management hadsought a 3 percent pay cut for 18 months, followed by restoration ofcurrent pay for the balance of a three-year pact. The guild had beenseeking yearly raises of 6 percent to 7 percent.   The newspaper's pay scale ranges from $625 a week for startingreporters to $895 for reporters with five years of experience.   Union members have been working without a contract since June 1.A strike would be the first by Sun-Times editorial workers in thenewspaper's 40-year history.   The Sun-Times says it must control costs to remain competitivewith the larger Chicago Tribune.  </TEXT></DOC>